Error: var initializer 'base' must be a constant numeric expression
   ╭─[ tests/golden/fixtures/syntax-var-relative-bare-ident-err/input.k65:2:12 ]
   │
 2 │ var next = base + 0x100
   │            ──────┬─────  
   │                  ╰─────── non-constant identifier `base`
   │ 
   │ Help 1: `var` initializers fix the variable's address at compile time, so the right-hand side must reduce to a number; replace `base` with a literal address, an arithmetic expression over literals, or a `const` that resolves to a number
   │ 
   │ Help 2: 'base' is a fixed-address var; if you meant its address, write `&&base` (e.g. `&&base + offset`)
   │ 
   │ Note: K816 `var = expr` declares a memory-located variable at the address `expr` evaluates to. That address is baked into every reference at compile time — there is no runtime computation to fall back on, so identifiers without a compile-time value cannot appear here.
